metadata.name: Chaos Culture #311
metadata.description:
"Chaos Culture" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

《西遊記》第一回:「混沌未分天地亂，茫茫渺渺無人見。」

Chaos Culture is the final chapter of this series. There is a legend in the East that before Pan Gu opened up the sky and created the earth, the world was a chaotic place, and no one knew its appearance. And I have always been fascinated by this mythical story since he was a child.

These three works have a father-son relationship, Research > Memory > Culture, with each work re-growing through the remnants of the previous work, depending on its image. From the beginning of the creative coding, I like the concept of recursion the most. Here I experiment with my central thinking through this iterative relationship so that the work is not only the shadow of the artist but also the pulling force of repetition.

"混沌" Chaos in Eastern culture represents the initial state of things. This state is consistent with what we believe in generative art: Anything can happen if different forces are applied. Letting chaos grow out of order and then destroying it, the iterative process, is like my usual dialogue with myself, and maybe it's all just a diary.

Through these three series of works, whether I can eventually find everything in my childhood fantasy, I am not sure yet. The only thing I can be sure of is that I will continue to explore.

metadata.name: One Tezo Drawings #29
metadata.description:
The One Tezo Drawings project is a variation of the “Desenhos de um Real” project (2006- ). In it, the artist sets the price of his work by making a rational calculation, equating his artistic production with a consumer good detached from the art world .
In this case, the calculation is based on the amount charged per hour of work from the minimum wage in the United States. Thus, a drawing that took X hours to produce (Wt) will have its price fixed at USD 15.00 * Wt divided by the value in Dollars of one Tezo (Dt) at the time of publication. But for the final price to be 1.00 Tez, the total production time value (Wt) will be divided by the number of editions (Ed). Therefore, the number of editions is defined by the following formula: 1.00 Tez = (Wt*15/Dt)/Ed ==> 

Ed=Wt*15/Dt 

For example, if a drawing took 10 hours to produce, the number of editions (worth 1.00 Tez each) will be: 10*15/2.01 = 75

For this particular project:
Permutation of 10 to 16 mirrored layers.

Wt= 8
Dt= 1.83
Ed= 8*15/1.83 = 65

Press J or P to save a 1500x1500px image

metadata.name: Speed of Dark #26
metadata.description:
Simple shapes, when strewn broadly and systematically, suggest the presence of infinite creative possibilities and are capable of portraying a visceral excitement felt by mixing the energy of light with the contemplation of dark.

This exercise has been repeated for ages, and its relevance will remain for as long as light may meet dark. The silhouettes of Stonehenge battling against a bright sky, the wabi-sabi placement of rocks in a Japanese garden hugged by methodical raking, the play of shadows in Plato's Allegory of the Cave, and the playfully arranged cut-outs of collage or chemical photogram — these all attest to the unending dynamism of form when imbued with light and the contrast of its absence.

As absence and darkness are made visible, the trail of their path conveys a speed as fast as light, and dark shapes that are no less important than the brightest figures. A symbiotic coexistence of these forces was born with the universe – and a delicate balance remains between the powerful glare of light and the stealthy speed of dark.

Inspired by photograms and a little-known series by documentary photographer William Klein, Speed of Dark references the visual language of the darkroom and the history of photography as an underlying analog for how an emerging art medium can harness simple elements to create evocative expressions.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #294
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

metadata.name: Rehash 10000 #79
metadata.description:
This project was supposed to be released in celebration of fxhash reaching 10,000 projects since its inception, but it's hard to celebrate when war breaks out and innocent people fear for their lives. Please go ahead and mint as many iterations as you like for free. If you feel the art is worth more than 0 tez, you are welcome to donate to the Tezos fund to support our Ukrainian friends (KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx).

Each mint combines 5 of my previous 14 fxhash projects into a drug-induced distorted vision of life in the Metaverse. This artwork is fully generative and was entirely hand-coded in 5333 lines of plain JavaScript code. Forever limited to 500 editions on the Tezos blockchain. London, February 2022.

metadata.name: Candles #2
metadata.description:
Why are you into NFT's? Chasing the profit or loving the art? The "Candles" project arises from this dilemma.

Once you mint, the market will open and randomly decide whether you win or lose. 
There is Dark and Light Mode and very rarely you will mint a Single Loop Trader Mode piece, which is by far the dullest version, and at the same time the rarest and so the most valuable... 
So question yourself, would I rather mint a dull and valuable piece, or a colorful piece of art to enjoy.

And oh, If you press "r" you will be able to see your profit (or loss) and toggle it on/off. just for fun :-)

@Elum0x, pure Javascript, Brussels 2022.

metadata.name: Fictional Cityscapes #64
metadata.description:
Some of the most stunning, and beloved, images are large cities, viewed from afar at the right angle, and preferably with some water in front. 

This project comes from my experiments with line art, and is slightly inspired by Hevey's amazing Dencity drop, which is on a different level to most generative art. 

The cities here are based on some fictional tower architecture and some unusual skies.
